Advantages and Disadvantages of Converting Credits to Swiss Francs
In the banking market, two offers for the conversion of loans into Swiss francs have already appeared, the main advantages being the exclusion of currency risk and the reduction of rates.
Disadvantages can come in a few years, when the variable interest rate can lead to higher rates.
The Bank of Transylvania has just completed the process of converting loans into francs granted by Volksbank, and Bancpost has announced a conversion offer for its own customers.
According to data accumulated by analysts of FinZoom financial portal, Bancpost offers three years of fixed interest at RON, 1.5%, the lowest on the market.
On the other hand, Transilvania Bank’s conversion offer was accepted by 83% of customers with franc credits due to two successive reductions: the balance was reduced by the value of the risk and management fees paid by the customer, then an additional reduction of 22.5% was applied to the balance in lei.
Both offers reduce the rates of their own customers, compared to how much they paid monthly in RON before the conversion.
Thus, Banca Transilvania reduced the rate by 42.5% and Bancpost by 33% in the first three years and, theoretically, by 18% in the following years.
Beneficiaries
The main advantage of the RON credit coverage in CHF is that the currency risk is eliminated, the consumer is protected from future increases in the franc, and the repayment of the credit will be made in the currency in which they collect their salary.
Another major advantage of both conversion offers is that there is no reassessment of the property, no additional guarantees are required and another proof of income.
In practice, there will be no further financial and legal analysis of the loan, nor will there be any additional costs as in the case of a refinancing.
Both banks also offer a discount on the monthly rate, compared to what customers paid before the conversion, equivalent in RON.
Risks
The problem is that the rate in the first years is made up more of the interest, and the customer refunds very little of the principal.
The Bancpost offer with very low interest rates in the first three years seems to be advantageous for customers.
However, it is not known how this interest will develop after three years.
The margin offered to customers can be greater than 3.25%, so in total, and the cost reduction is lower.
A possible risk for all loans in RON with variable interest rates is that the ROBOR index will increase significantly in the coming years (more than the Libor index - CHF).
For example, ROBOR at three months is now 1.44%, but in 2013 it had reached the value of 6%, in 2009, to over 15%, and in a few days of 2008 it exceeded 40%!
In addition, other costs, not mentioned in the initial offer, may also occur.
