On the occasion of the most anticipated meeting in recent years, Federal Reserve policymakers will spend two days this week around a 27-legged Honduran mahogany table to decide whether it is time to raise a key interest rate for the first time in nearly a decade.
Above them, at one end of the meeting hall of the central bank, will be seen a mural of the United States.
The map is meant to remind that Janet L. Yellen, the Fed’s president, and his colleagues must put the nation’s economic interests above all else.
The Central Bank has received a double burden from Congress: to maximize the employment rate of the U.S. labor force and maintain price stability.
But since the great economic crisis, the Fed leaders have confirmed that there is a third unwritten task: financial stability.
And this third task could be factor X in a decision too difficult to anticipate, which will be announced on Tuesday, and which will determine whether the U.S. economy is prepared to be dealt with by the unprecedented stimulus offered by the near-zero short-term interest rate in effect from the end of 2008.
Even if most of the data indicates a strong growing economy, recent turmoil in global financial markets could scare already cautious Fed officials into adding volatility by raising the benchmark rate on federal funds — even by just a quarter of a percentage point.
“Obviously, the labor market and inflation will be the first and main issues they will pursue,” said Lindsey M. Piegza, chief economist at brokerage firm Stifel Nicolaus & Co.
“But I think if they were to look for an excuse not to raise the interest rate, the growing uncertainty on the world market is enough to give them arguments to wait,” she said.
There is no consensus on the Fed’s decision, which in itself causes instability in the financial market.
About half of the economists recently polled by Bloomberg predicted an increase in the interest rate this week.
But financial markets expect the Fed to delay, a key indicator showing that the likelihood of growth is only 30%.
This would indicate a decline in the stock market if the Fed raises the interest rate, unless policymakers softened the blow by promising that it would take a long time until the next rise.
On Tuesday, the Dow Jones Industrial Average climbed 228.89 points, or 1.4%, to 16,599.85.
The advance was triggered by expectations that Fed decision makers will keep the interest rate stable this week, said John Lonski, chief economist at Moody's Capital Markets Research Group.
“It would be surprising if the Fed were to raise the interest rate at this point,” Lonski said.
If the Fed’s decision makers do this, “they should act in depth in their policies to avoid panic in financial markets.”
Other experts said an increase in the interest rate would calm financial markets as it would remove uncertainty about when the Fed would act.
Just a month ago, the Fed appeared to be about to raise the rate by 0.25% this month, the first small step toward slowly tightening monetary conditions that would confirm the strength of the U.S. recovery.
Yellen said in the spring and early summer that he expected interest rates to rise this year despite high objections from liberals that more economic progress would be needed.
Although job creation slowed in August, the growth of the labor market was solid this year.
The unemployment rate fell to 5.1% last month, the lowest percentage in more than seven years and close to the level considered by the Fed as total employment.
Salary gains have shown signs of growth.
And while inflation continued to fall short of the central bank’s annual target, the Fed’s decision makers said a key reason was the temporary effect of sharply falling oil prices.
The economy “can cope with higher rates and needs them, given the labor market tension,” said Ian Shepherdson, chief economist at Pantheon Macroeconomics.
But global financial markets began fibrillating at the end of this month after China devalued its currency.
The Dow Jones industrial average fell 16 percent below the record high in May, as investors feared a slowdown in the Chinese economy would drive down global growth.
The market has shrunk somewhat this month, with the Dow now hovering around 10% below its May high.
For Fed decision makers, market turmoil adds to the complex calculation of the moment of interest rate rise.
“Without what’s happened in the financial markets and the news about the weakening of the Chinese economy in recent weeks, it would be stronger at the meeting,” said Stephen D. Oliner, an experienced researcher at the UCLA Ziman Center for Real Estate and a former Fed official.
Now, he predicts that they will wait at least a month to better manage the effects.
"There is a lot of uncertainty about what the impact will be on the U.S. economy and there is almost no data to be based on later events in China," Oliner said.
The well-being of the global economy is not one of the major interests of the Fed, so it should practically not be taken into account when making decisions.
But in reality, the Fed has become the world’s monetary authority.
In recent years, the influence of the central bank has been enormous.
The simple allusion of then-President Ben S. Bernanke in 2013 that the Fed might “narrow” its monetary expansion triggered an earthquake in global markets.
In a world where markets and economies are increasingly crowded, it is expected that Fed officials will not only monitor progress in other areas, but also consult with other central banks and experts to better interpret the world economy.
His decision-making process is “more art than science,” said Zachary Karabell, head of global strategy at wealth management firm Envestnet Inc.
Jeffrey Lacker, president of the Federal Reserve Bank of Richmond, Va., said this month that “the Fed has a history of overreacting to changes in the financial market that seem unrelated to economic fundamentals.”
Lacker, a voting member of the Federal Open Market Commission, a decision-making body that supported the rise in the interest rate, gave the 1998-99 decisions as an example.
A financial crisis that affected Asia led the Fed to cut the benchmark rate by 0.75% in three meetings, “despite the implications of limited identification for U.S. development,” Lacker said.
A year later, the Fed officials returned to those declines.
The Fed should put the issue of financial stability first only in the event of a major crisis, such as the 2008 market earthquake, said Adam S. Posen, a former member of the Bank of England’s interest rate-setting committee.
The latest agitated period does not rise far to that level, he said.
“We certainly don’t want to get into a situation where we’re afraid of rising interest rates because markets are angry,” said Posen, president of the Peterson Institute for International Economics.
The Federal Reserve Act still holds the double mandate and does not mention financial stability and, until something changes in this regard, I do not think it should take premature action.
