Weight-reducing surgery could be useful for diabetics with mild obesity
The benefits of weight-reduction surgery in people with mild obesity with type 2 diabetes could be maintained for at least five years, according to a new study.
It’s still premature to say whether mildly obese diabetics live longer after weight loss surgery than those who follow nonsurgical treatments.
“It takes a long time to centralize mortality data,” said Dr. Robin Blackstone, a specialist in obesity surgery, as she wrote an article about the new study in JAMA Surgery.
Operations for weight loss, also called bariatric surgery, use various methods to reduce the stomach.
They reduce the feeling of hunger and limit the body’s ability to absorb food.
Over the years, bariatric surgery has proven effective in the treatment of type 2 diabetes, but most studies have been conducted on people with morbid obesity, with a body mass index (BMI) of 35 or higher.
BMI, a unit of weight in relation to height, is considered normal in the range of 18.5-24.9.
A BMI of at least 25 indicates that a person is overweight and people with BMI over 30 are considered obese.
You can calculate your BMI by going to: 1.usa.gov/1D0ZqDv.
For the new study, researchers at Taiwan’s Min-Sheng General Hospital used data collected after 2007 in a trial comparing two types of bariatric surgery — gastric bypass and gastrectomy in the sleeve — in medical treatment of type 2 diabetes in people with mild obesity.
Average BMI in people who had surgery decreased from 31 to 24.5 by the end of the fifth year of the study.
Meanwhile, BMI in people who received nonsurgical treatments for diabetes remained almost at the same level, i.e. 29.
Of those who had surgery, diabetes was completely cured at 36% and partially at 28%.
In the group treated by medical methods, by comparison, diabetes was completely cured in only 1% and partially in only 2% of the subjects.
In addition, blood pressure control, triglycerides and “bad” LDL cholesterol “were generally better in the surgical group,” the authors concluded.
The researchers also monitored blood levels of hemoglobin A1c, which reflects blood glucose levels over time.
The researchers write that the optimal level of hemoglobin A1c is below 7%.
After surgery, the average level of hemoglobin A1c decreased from about 9% to about 6%.
However, in the group treated by medical methods, it remained at about 8%.
But this improved “glycemic control”—reflected by improved A1c hemoglobin levels—did not reduce the five-year mortality rate, according to lead researcher Dr. Chih-Cheng Hsu and colleagues.
The research team also compared the average results associated with the two types of surgery.
In the fifth year, compared to the group with gastrectomy in the sleeve, the group with complete bypass surgery lost more weight (18.7 versus 14.2 kg), recorded more significant decreases in BMI (7.4 versus 5.1) and A1c haemoglobin (3.1% versus 2.1%), and the group with complete bypass surgery lost more weight (18.7 versus 14.2 kg).
Although the new study does not indicate a survival benefit or surgery after five years, there is evidence from a study of overweight people in Sweden that surgery prolongs life, says Blackstone, of the University of Arizona, Faculty of Medicine - Phoenix.
In the Swedish study, obese people who had bariatric surgery were about 29% less likely to die after 15 years, compared with a group that tried more conventional methods.
Although the new study did not indicate a survival benefit in patients undergoing surgery, Blackstone said it is an optimistic aspect for people with BMI below 35 interested in the procedure.
“This is where this work is critical because it states that this surgery is safe in the lower BMI group,” without increasing the risk of death or kidney disease, she says.
Blackstone added that patients and their doctors should start taking the weight seriously when the patient’s BMI reaches 27-30.
“I think we’re waiting too long to urge people to take this aspect seriously,” she said.
I think that once they have accumulated these genetic changes that have short-circuited their bodies predisposing them to obesity and diabetes, it is extremely difficult to get back to normal.
