A recent study of more than 2,000 high school students who had symptoms of depression concluded that if the patient is surrounded by enough friends “with a healthy mood,” his chances of recovery are doubled.
Similarly, for people who are not depressed, a circle of mentally healthy friends halve the likelihood of mental disorders.
Of course, for friendship to have effect, it must first be accessible.
In this era of social media-dominated communication, where the emphasis is on style rather than substance, the immediate nature of the response often takes precedence over meaningful contact.
Our digital lives have doubled the need to create the appearance of a strong personality, open to fun and success, even if in reality it is isolation that dominates.
This superficial success is dominated by what psychologists call extrinsic values; money, image, social status, all at the cost of intrinsic values – our inner desire for personal development and friendship – which further affects our mental health.
