The government approved on Wednesday the "National Immigration Strategy for 2015-2018" and the "Agency Plan for the current year", documents considered to be "another stage that Romania is going through as part of efforts to modernize the process of immigration management on the national territory", according to a press release.
The strategy aims to effectively manage the phenomenon of immigration, including general strategic objectives, specific objectives and the direction of action that reflects the policies established at European level, adapted to national realities.
In view of the problems faced by the states in the immediate vicinity of Romania, measures for the unitary and coherent management of situations caused by the possible occurrence of an influx of illegal immigrants on the territory of Romania, generated by situations of crisis of a political, social, economic or military nature are considered.
"The Romanian authorities will contribute to the creation of a flexible admission system, but at the same time, they will pay special attention to citizens from countries with migration potential or that may affect national security," the source added.
The strategy identifies a number of factors that can influence immigration and asylum, including maintaining the conflict situation in Syria, reactivating the conflict in Iraq, maintaining an unstable situation in the neighbouring areas of Romania (Ukraine, Transnistria), perpetuating and increasing the intensity of the Israeli-Palestinian armed conflict.
On the other hand, the document also sets some general strategic objectives related to immigration, such as: promotion of legal migration, more rigorous controls of the legality of the residence of third-country nationals on the territory of Romania and the appropriate application of removal measures and restrictive measures, improvement of the national asylum system.
The national strategy shall also include specific objectives relevant to the transposition and implementation of the general strategic objectives.
These include: facilitating access on the territory of Romania of third-country nationals who meet the needs of employment, promoting access of third-country nationals to higher education institutions in Romania for the areas and professions identified as deficient.
Regarding the 2015 Action Plan, the Government considers it to be “a means of establishing concrete activities that will lead to the creation of a flexible system to stop the growing migration phenomenon”.
